{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567540"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:03:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:03:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19119"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19119"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.05,0.78,0.1,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11853"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82576"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11853"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19119"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67741"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"104"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27816"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28036"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28037"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82576"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with progressive shortness of breath and chest discomfort. He underwent coronary artery bypass grafting five days ago and was discharged yesterday. He has a history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes. His medications include aspirin, metoprolol, and metformin. On examination, he appears unwell and anxious. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 85/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 95% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Bearing in mind the likely diagnosis, which one of the following combinations of physical signs would be expected?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bradycardia, raised jugular venous pressure and peripheral cyanosis","Hypotension, displaced apex beat and pulsus alternans","Hypotension, muffled heart sounds and distended neck veins","Tachycardia, muffled heart sounds and pulmonary crackles","Tachypnoea, chest wall crepitus and muffled heart sounds"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of cardiac tamponade following recent cardiac surgery. If this was the case, the combination of physical signs that would be sought are those that make up Beck\u0027s triad.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypotension, muffled heart sounds, and distended neck veins\u003C/strong\u003E constitute Beck\u0027s triad, which is the classic presentation of cardiac tamponade. These signs occur due to the accumulation of fluid in the pericardial space, causing compression of the heart chambers and reduced cardiac output. The patient\u0027s recent cardiac surgery puts him at high risk for this complication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETachycardia, muffled heart sounds, and pulmonary crackles\u003C/strong\u003E are more suggestive of congestive heart failure. While tachycardia and muffled heart sounds may be present in tamponade, pulmonary crackles are not typical features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBradycardia, raised jugular venous pressure, and peripheral cyanosis\u003C/strong\u003E might be seen in right heart failure or superior vena cava syndrome. Bradycardia would be unusual in tamponade, where tachycardia is typically present as a compensatory mechanism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETachypnoea, chest wall crepitus, and muffled heart sounds\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest pneumothorax or surgical emphysema, which are different post-operative complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypotension, displaced apex beat, and pulsus alternans\u003C/strong\u003E are more consistent with severe left ventricular dysfunction. In tamponade, the apex beat is typically difficult to palpate due to the surrounding fluid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECardiac tamponade is a clinical diagnosis that requires urgent intervention, typically with pericardiocentesis. Other findings may include pulsus paradoxus (a fall in systolic blood pressure \u0026gt;10 mmHg during inspiration) and electrical alternans on ECG. The presence of Beck\u0027s triad in a post-cardiac surgery patient should prompt immediate action to prevent cardiovascular collapse.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Beck\u0027s triad (hypotension, muffled heart sounds, and distended neck veins) is the classic presentation of cardiac tamponade.","Cardiac tamponade is a clinical diagnosis that requires urgent intervention.","Recent cardiothoracic surgery is a significant risk factor for cardiac tamponade."],"references":["Jensen et al. Cardiac tamponade: a clinical challenge, E-Journal of Cardiology Practice - Volume 1, 2017, https://www.escardio.org/Journals/E-Journal-of-Cardiology-Practice/Volume-15/Cardiac-tamponade-a-clinical-challenge"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67741"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19119"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67741"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-30T08:23:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-30T08:24:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11853"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82576"}}},"m